# Canonical scenario-hash canonicalization — scenario-block-only
#
# Pins the upstream-of-everything contract for what a "scenario hash"
# names, and how the two surfaces that carry it (the `@scenario_hash:<hex>`
# tag on disk under `features/`, and the `scenarios[].hash` field on a
# shop-msg payload on the wire) MUST agree.
#
# Vocabulary (load-bearing, used by every scenario below):
#
# - "canonical hash algorithm" — sha256 of the canonical hash text,
#   truncated to the first 16 hex characters (lower-case). This algorithm
#   is already in use under the `@scenario_hash:<hex>` tag format on disk
#   and in `scenarios[].hash` on the wire; this file does NOT redefine it.
#
# - "canonical hash text" — the text input to the canonical hash
#   algorithm. The canonicalization rule below pins what this text is.
#
# - "scenario block" — the contiguous lines belonging to a single
#   `Scenario:` or `Scenario Outline:` declaration: the lines from the
#   `Scenario:` / `Scenario Outline:` keyword line through the last step
#   line (and Examples block, if any) of that scenario, together with the
#   tag lines (`@<tag>`) attached immediately above the keyword line if
#   any. Adjacent `Scenario:` declarations and the `Feature:` header line
#   are NOT part of the block.
#
# - "scenario-block-only canonicalization" — the canonical hash text for
#   a scenario block is derived solely from the scenario block's lines;
#   the `Feature:` header line of the enclosing feature file is NOT part
#   of the canonical hash text.
#
# - "Feature-line-included canonicalization" — an alternative rule under
#   which the canonical hash text includes the `Feature:` header line of
#   the enclosing feature file. This file rejects this rule (see
#   scenario 117-D).
#
# PO call (this file): the canonical rule is SCENARIO-BLOCK-ONLY.
# Rationale: the `@scenario_hash:<hex>` tag is per-scenario; a tag-local
# canonicalization survives benign edits to the `Feature:` header (typo
# fix, feature-title clarification) without invalidating every scenario
# hash in the file. Feature-line-included canonicalization couples
# per-scenario hash identity to a file-level header the scenario does
# not name, which is the surface lead-2ca observed in the wild
# (Feature-line-included `scenarios[].hash` carried by shop-msg `send`
# disagreeing with scenario-block-only `@scenario_hash:` tags on disk).
#
# Open architectural choice DEFERRED to the architect at dispatch:
# WHICH BC owns the canonicalization implementation. Probable targets:
# (a) shopsystem-messaging — `shop-msg send`'s `_build_scenario_payload`
#     and `_compute_scenario_hash` paths today wrap with a `Feature:`
#     header and hash the wrapped text; this is the on-wire side of the
#     disagreement (lead-2ca evidence: 07d405ae455c5553 vs 641bae76c069bf5b).
# (b) shopsystem-scenarios — owner of `compute_scenario_hash`; the
#     canonicalization rule strips `@scenario_hash:` lines but is silent
#     on whether the `Feature:` line should be in the input at all.
# (c) shopsystem-templates — owner of the `@scenario_hash:` tag tooling
#     and the role templates that direct authors and reviewers to compute
#     hashes; could carry the rule statement.
# The scenarios below are stated in vocabulary that pins behavior
# regardless of which BC houses the implementation.


Scenario: a scenario block on disk that carries an "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tag, when hashed under the canonical algorithm with scenario-block-only canonicalization, produces a hex value equal to the tag value (happy-path on-disk equality)
  Given a feature file under "features/" whose contents include a "Feature:" header line and at least one scenario block
  And the scenario block carries an "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tag immediately above its "Scenario:" or "Scenario Outline:" keyword line
  When the scenario block's lines (scenario-block-only canonicalization, "Feature:" header NOT included) are fed to the canonical hash algorithm
  Then the resulting 16-hex-character lower-case value is equal byte-for-byte to the "<hex>" value carried in the on-disk "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tag
  And the equality holds regardless of how many other scenario blocks are present in the same feature file
  And the equality holds regardless of the literal text of the enclosing "Feature:" header line


Scenario: the "scenarios[].hash" value carried in a shop-msg payload for a given scenario block is byte-for-byte equal to the "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tag value on disk for the same scenario block (wire / on-disk equality)
  Given a scenario block that is pinned on disk under "features/" of some BC shop with an "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tag
  And a shop-msg payload (assign_scenarios or request_bugfix on outbound dispatch; work_done.scenario_hashes on inbound reconciliation) that carries a hash for that same scenario block in the "scenarios[].hash" field (or, for work_done, in the "scenario_hashes" list)
  When the on-disk tag value and the on-wire hash value are compared as 16-hex-character lower-case strings
  Then the two values are byte-for-byte equal
  And the equality is achieved by both surfaces computing the canonical hash text under scenario-block-only canonicalization and applying the canonical hash algorithm, NOT by post-hoc substring matching of the carried gherkin against the on-disk file
  And reconciliation (lead-side enumeration of dispatched hashes against the BC's "@scenario_hash:" tag set, and BC-side pre-emit recomputation per ADR-010) is permitted to compare carried hash values to on-disk tag values directly, expecting equality


Scenario: the canonical hash text for a scenario block is derived from the scenario block's lines alone, without the "Feature:" header line of the enclosing feature file (canonicalization rule pinning — scenario-block-only is canonical)
  Given any scenario block, whether authored as a fresh scenario or extracted from an existing feature file
  When the canonical hash text for that scenario block is determined
  Then the canonical hash text is built from the scenario block's lines only — its tag lines (if any) immediately above the "Scenario:" or "Scenario Outline:" keyword line, the keyword line itself, the step lines, and the "Examples:" block lines (if any) — and does NOT include the "Feature:" header line of any enclosing feature file
  And blank lines within the scenario block are dropped by the canonicalization (consistent with the existing "scenarios hash" rule that strips per-line whitespace and drops blank lines)
  And lines whose stripped form starts with "@scenario_hash:" are dropped by the canonicalization (consistent with the existing "scenarios hash" rule, so the tag-embedding-its-own-hash chicken-and-egg resolves naturally)
  And the rule is the same on the disk-authoring side (the value an "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tag carries) and on the wire-payload side (the value a shop-msg payload's "scenarios[].hash" carries); there is exactly one canonical hash text per scenario block, not one per surface


Scenario: a benign edit to the "Feature:" header line of a feature file (typo fix in the feature title, rewording of the feature description) does NOT invalidate any "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tag on any scenario block within the file (Feature-line edit invariance — adversarial)
  Given a feature file under "features/" whose contents include a "Feature:" header line and at least one scenario block carrying an "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tag
  And the on-disk tag value of each such block matches the canonical scenario-block-only hash of that block (per the happy-path equality scenario above)
  When the "Feature:" header line is edited in a way that does not touch any scenario block (e.g., a typo in the feature title is fixed; a feature-description paragraph immediately under "Feature:" is rephrased)
  Then for every scenario block in the file, the canonical hash text under scenario-block-only canonicalization is byte-for-byte unchanged
  And consequently the canonical hash value of every scenario block is byte-for-byte unchanged
  And the existing "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tags on disk remain valid without any rewrite
  And this invariance is the load-bearing property that makes scenario-block-only canonicalization the safer rule: a Feature-line-included rule would invalidate every "@scenario_hash:" tag in the file on any "Feature:" edit, which contradicts the per-scenario identity the tag is meant to carry


Scenario: an edit to the body of a scenario block (any step text added, removed, or modified; any tag added or removed other than "@scenario_hash:"; any "Examples:" row added, removed, or modified) MUST cause the canonical hash recomputation to differ from the on-disk "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tag value (integrity / scenario-text edit detection — adversarial)
  Given a feature file under "features/" containing a scenario block whose on-disk "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tag value matches the canonical scenario-block-only hash of that block
  When any line of the scenario block is edited such that the canonicalized form of the block (after per-line whitespace strip, dropping blank lines, and dropping "@scenario_hash:" lines) changes by at least one byte
  Then a fresh canonical scenario-block-only hash of the edited block produces a hex value that is NOT equal to the on-disk "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tag value
  And reconciliation tooling that compares the recomputed hash against the on-disk tag MUST flag the disagreement (the BC Reviewer's pre-emit recomputation per ADR-010 and the lead-architect's reconciliation pass on "work_done" are both authorized to treat this disagreement as a hard failure)
  And this integrity property holds whether the edit is a deliberate scenario revision (legitimate — the author MUST then update the "@scenario_hash:" tag to match the new canonical hash), an accidental scenario-body edit, or an attempted bit-flip in the block's text; the canonicalization rule does not distinguish between these and reports disagreement uniformly


Scenario: a scenario block that does NOT carry an "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tag is permitted on disk under "features/" and is NOT required to be tagged by the canonicalization contract (tag-absent scenarios are silently allowed)
  Given a feature file under "features/" containing one or more scenario blocks
  And at least one scenario block in the file has no "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tag in its tag lines (or has no tag lines at all)
  When tooling that consumes the canonicalization contract (reconciliation, pre-emit recomputation, hash-by-value lookup against "features/") walks the file
  Then the tag-absent scenario block is silently permitted: no error, no warning required by the canonicalization contract alone
  And the tag-absent scenario block is NOT addressable by hash-value lookup (no "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tag carrying its canonical hash exists on disk, so a hash-by-value grep cannot reach it)
  And the canonicalization contract does NOT require that every scenario block under "features/" carry an "@scenario_hash:" tag; tag-presence enforcement is an orthogonal policy decision (e.g., per-BC, per-feature-file, or per-dispatch-discipline) and is OUT OF SCOPE for this file
  And the canonicalization contract DOES require, for every scenario block that DOES carry an "@scenario_hash:<hex>" tag, that the on-disk tag value equal the canonical scenario-block-only hash of the block (per the happy-path equality scenario above)
